'''Hwanghae''' (''Hwanghae-do'' {{IPA-ko|hwaŋ.ɦɛ.do|}}) was one of the [[Eight Provinces of Korea]] during the [[Joseon]]. Hwanghae was located in the northwest of Korea. The provincial capital was [[Haeju]]. 
The [[Regions of Korea|regional name]] for the province was Haeseo.

==History==<!-- This section is linked from [[Provinces of Korea]] -->
In 1395, the province was organized as P'unghae (''P'unghae-do;'' 풍해도; 豊海道).  In 1417, the province was renamed Hwanghae.  The name derived from the names of the two principal cities of Hwangju (황주; 黃州) and Haeju (해주; 海州).

In 1895, the province was reorganized into the [[Provinces of Korea#Districts of Late Joseon|Districts]] of Haeju (''Haeju-bu;'' 해주부; 海州府) in the west and [[Kaesong|Gaeseong]] (''Gaeseong-bu;'' 개성부; 開城府) in the east, but in 1896, a new system of thirteen provinces was established, and Hwanghae Province was reconstituted.

In 1945, Korea was [[Division of Korea|divided]] into [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[United States|American]] zones of occupation, north and south respectively of the [[38th parallel north|38th parallel]].  The southernmost part of Hwanghae (around the towns of [[Ongjin County, South Hwanghae|Ongjin]] and [[Yonan County]]) was cut off from the rest of the province by the dividing line and joined [[Gyeonggi Province]] in the southern half of the country.  In 1948, Hwanghae and Gyeonggi Provinces became parts of the new countries of [[North Korea|North]] and [[South Korea]] respectively.

In 1953, at the end of the [[Korean War]], the [[Northern Limit Line]] was established, which marked the [[maritime boundary]] between North and South Korea.  The line runs between the mainland portion of Gyeonggi Province that had been part of Hwanghae before 1945, and the adjacent offshore islands (the largest of which is [[Baengnyeongdo]]).  As a result, the mainland portion reverted to North Korean control, while the islands remained a part of South Korea.  (Since 1999, North Korea has claimed a more southerly [[Military Demarcation Line|Maritime Military Demarcation Line]], which would make the islands a part of North Korea as well.  Disputes between North and South Korean naval vessels often occur in this area.)

In 1954, North Korea's Hwanghae Province was divided into [[North Hwanghae Province|North]] and [[South Hwanghae Province]]s.

==Geography==
Hwanghae was bounded by [[Pyongan Province|Pyeongan Province]] (after 1896 [[South Pyongan Province|South Pyeongan]]) on the north, [[Gangwon Province (historical)|Gangwon Province]] on the east, [[Gyeonggi Province]] on the south, and the [[Yellow Sea]] on the west.

